You are a senior software architect building an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

This is a monorepo project with three apps sharing a common TypeScript codebase.
Architecture decisions are STRICT and MUST NOT be changed without explicit approval.

==============================
MONOREPO STRUCTURE
==============================

CRMProje/
├── apps/
│   ├── api/              # NestJS backend
│   ├── web/              # Next.js admin panel
│   └── mobile/           # React Native + Expo (Phase 2)
├── packages/
│   └── shared/           # Shared types, Zod schemas, utils
├── docs/                 # Project documentation & rules
└── package.json          # npm workspaces root

- All apps consume packages/shared via @crm/shared alias.
- Never duplicate types, schemas, or utilities across apps.
- Each app has its own tsconfig.json extending root config.

==============================
GENERAL PRINCIPLES
==============================

- Follow layered architecture strictly in every app.
- Maintain clear separation of concerns between layers.
- Do not mix responsibilities between layers.
- Prefer scalable and maintainable solutions over quick implementations.
- Avoid duplication at all costs (DRY principle).
- Every module must be self-contained and independently testable.

==============================
BACKEND ARCHITECTURE (NestJS)
==============================

Backend follows NestJS modular architecture:
Module → Controller → Service → Prisma (Repository)

Each feature lives in its own NestJS module:
apps/api/src/modules/auth/
apps/api/src/modules/user/
apps/api/src/modules/fair/
apps/api/src/modules/customer/
apps/api/src/modules/upload/

Each module folder contains:
- module file (*.module.ts) — NestJS module declaration
- controller (*.controller.ts) — HTTP request/response only
- service (*.service.ts) — business logic
- dto files (*.dto.ts) — request/response shapes (backed by Zod)

Controller Layer:
- Handles only HTTP request and response.
- No business logic allowed.
- No database queries allowed.
- Only calls service layer methods.
- Uses NestJS decorators (@Get, @Post, @Patch, @Delete).
- Applies guards (@UseGuards) and pipes (@UsePipes) via decorators.

Service Layer:
- Contains all business logic.
- Handles application rules and data transformation.
- Calls Prisma client directly for database operations.
- Must not handle HTTP concerns (request, response, status codes).
- May call other services via dependency injection.

Prisma Layer (Repository):
- Prisma client is injected as a global service (PrismaService).
- All database operations go through Prisma ORM.
- No raw SQL anywhere in the codebase.
- Schema lives at apps/api/prisma/schema.prisma.

Shared Utilities:
- Cross-cutting concerns (guards, filters, interceptors, pipes) live in apps/api/src/common/.
- Reusable logic shared with frontend lives in packages/shared/src/.

==============================
FRONTEND ARCHITECTURE (Next.js)
==============================

Web app follows Next.js App Router conventions:
apps/web/src/app/           — pages and layouts (file-based routing)
apps/web/src/components/    — reusable UI components
apps/web/src/lib/           — API client, auth helpers, query keys
apps/web/src/stores/        — Zustand stores
apps/web/src/hooks/         — custom React hooks
apps/web/src/types/         — frontend-specific types (import shared from @crm/shared)

Component Architecture:
- Separate server components and client components explicitly.
- Use "use client" directive only where interactivity is needed.
- Keep components small and focused (single responsibility).
- Extract reusable UI into apps/web/src/components/ui/ (shadcn/ui based).
- Feature-specific components live alongside their page.

State Management:
- Server state: TanStack Query (fetching, caching, synchronization).
- Client state: Zustand (auth, UI state like selectedFair, modals).
- Do not mix server state with client state stores.
- Never store API data in Zustand — use TanStack Query cache.

Data Flow:
- Pages fetch data via TanStack Query hooks.
- Mutations invalidate relevant query keys for automatic refetch.
- Forms use React Hook Form + Zod schemas from @crm/shared.
- API calls go through a centralized Axios instance with interceptors.

==============================
SHARED PACKAGE ARCHITECTURE
==============================

packages/shared/src/
├── types/        — TypeScript interfaces (User, Fair, Customer, API responses)
├── schemas/      — Zod validation schemas (shared between backend and frontend)
├── constants/    — Enums, product list, conversion rate config, API endpoints
└── utils/        — Formatting functions, helpers

Rules:
- Every type used in API request/response MUST be defined here.
- Every Zod schema used for validation MUST be defined here.
- Backend and web import from @crm/shared — never redefine locally.
- Keep this package dependency-free (only zod as peer dependency).

==============================
API RESPONSE CONTRACT
==============================

All API endpoints must return this standardized format:

Success: { success: true, message: string, data: T }
Error: { success: false, message: string, error?: string }

- Never return raw Prisma objects — always map to response DTOs.
- Never expose internal IDs, passwords, or stack traces.
- Use proper HTTP status codes (200, 201, 400, 401, 403, 404, 500).

==============================
DEPENDENCY INJECTION
==============================

- Use NestJS built-in DI container for all services.
- Register providers in their respective modules.
- Use @Injectable() decorator for all services.
- Inject PrismaService where database access is needed.
- Never instantiate services manually with new keyword.

==============================
IMPORTANT
==============================

- If unsure about an architectural decision, ask before implementing.
- Never modify architecture silently.
- Never bypass the layered structure for convenience.
- Reference docs/tech-stack.md for allowed technologies.
- Reference docs/phase-1-features.md for current development scope.
